    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d164bfa5-1044-431f-bd22-70d46b7327a1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 34-year-old woman from the Czech Republic who looks tired and uncomfortable during attacks, often preferring a dim, quiet room because light makes the headache worse with photophobia. She describes recurrent migraine headaches with nausea and sometimes vomiting, and says the pain can become throbbing and one-sided during worse episodes. She also reports that routine physical activity such as climbing stairs or brisk walking tends to worsen the pain during an attack, so she keeps still and limits screen time; between episodes she appears generally well and neurologically intact on basic examination.\n\nShe works full-time in an administrative office role and usually manages a structured weekday routine. Outside work, {patientName} enjoys long periods of computer-based crafting and online design hobbies, attends occasional loud live music events, and likes weekend coffee outings with a close friend. She has noticed that prolonged screen exposure, bright flickering lights, loud noise, missed meals during busy hobby sessions, and sometimes red wine at social events can precede headaches. She lives with her partner and says her social life is good overall, but migraine days force her to cancel plans at short notice because of headache, nausea, and light sensitivity.\n\nAt home, {patientName} tries practical self-management measures such as resting in a dark room and avoiding bright light during attacks. She has noticed occasional burping and stomach upset during some headache episodes, which she associates with the nausea. She does not describe focal weakness or other unusual neurological symptoms, and her main complaint remains recurrent migraine headache with associated nausea and intermittent vomiting.\n\nFamily life is important to her, and she worries about the way these headaches disrupt work attendance and time with loved ones. She reports that migraine seems to run in her family: her mother has migraine, and a maternal aunt has a history of migraine as well. She also notes that her mother has anxiety, and that stress and poor sleep often seem to make headaches easier to trigger for her."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:32e8f0d4-0428-45c0-b36a-69760340d2b8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports a history of recurrent headaches beginning in adulthood, with episodes marked by headache, photophobia, nausea, and occasional vomiting. She says some attacks feel predominantly right-sided and throbbing, lasting from several hours into the next day. She specifically notes that routine activity makes the headache worse and that she prefers to lie still in a dark room until the attack settles. She denies prior stroke, seizure disorder, head trauma, persistent focal neurologic deficits, or prior hospitalization for headache.\n\nHer background medical history includes treated hypothyroidism, seasonal allergic rhinitis, generalized anxiety symptoms, and menstrual irregularity with suspected hormonally triggered headaches around the perimenstrual period. The anxiety and hormonal pattern are clinically relevant because stress, sleep disruption, and estrogen fluctuation can predispose to migraine attacks. She takes levothyroxine regularly for thyroid replacement, uses cetirizine during pollen seasons, and uses a combined oral contraceptive containing ethinylestradiol/levonorgestrel for contraception; she has noticed that headaches can cluster around the hormone-free interval. Estrogen-containing contraceptives are not the sole cause of migraine, but hormonal exposure can contribute to headache susceptibility in some patients.\n\nLifestyle-wise, {patientName} works at a desk job, sleeps somewhat irregularly during busy workweeks, and drinks coffee most mornings. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol only occasionally. She has noticed that prolonged screen time during hobbies, loud concerts, skipped meals, poor sleep, and sometimes red wine can trigger attacks. She has not been diagnosed with irritable bowel syndrome, though she does report gastrointestinal upset with some headaches, including nausea and occasional burping.\n\nFamily history is notable for migraine in her mother and maternal aunt, and for anxiety disorder in her mother. This pattern reinforces a familial predisposition to migraine and related neurologic symptom vulnerability."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
